  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-11980">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 1. </span>
      Do the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-11980 mb-requirement-id-11981">
        (a) Explain radiation and the difference between ionizing and
        nonionizing radiation. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/FrVUJ2c_Rwc?si=3e61M3Jbgg9w3ToV"
          target="_blank"
          >Radiation &amp; You (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/uJ3ea9fa6CA?si=lpSg7dn3koa5wAOV"
          target="_blank"
          >IDTIMWYTIM: Radiation (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-11980 mb-requirement-id-11982">
        (b) Explain the ALARA principle and the measures required by law to
        minimize these risks. Describe what safety requirements you will need to
        consider while performing the requirements in this merit badge. <br /><i
          >Resource:</i
        >
        <a
          href="https://www.cdc.gov/radiation-health/safety/alara.html"
          target="_blank"
        >
          The ALARA Principle (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-11980 mb-requirement-id-11983">
        (c) Describe the radiation hazard symbol and explain where it should be
        used. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/Nss1nl56fPo?si=gjiyC4gVAGL9CMsk"
          target="_blank"
          >Radiation Hazard Symbol (video)</a
        >
        <br />
        <a
          href="https://www.iaea.org/newscenter/news/how-are-universal-ionizing-radiation-symbols-used-around-the-world/"
          target="_blank"
          >How Are Universal Ionizing Radiation Symbols Used Around the World?
          (website)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-11980 mb-requirement-id-11984">
        (d) Explain how we are exposed to ionizing radiation from outside the
        earth as well as on earth every day. List four examples of Naturally
        Occurring Radioactive Materials (NORM) that are in your house or grocery
        store and explain why they are radioactive. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/-9gD6FMivTQ?si=O-BCuqRKLgTMGZpg"
          target="_blank"
          >Five Radioactive Products We Use Every Day (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/FZtR3UEEkXA?si=jC5BJJVPgtDS4nK3"
          target="_blank"
          >Your Grocery Store is Radioactive (and So Is Everything Else)
          (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/_bKbMARsE-4?si=ba7MFiT_UCPs9WZj"
          target="_blank"
          >The Mystery of High-Energy Cosmic Rays (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-11980 mb-requirement-id-11985">
        (e) Explain the difference between radiation exposure and contamination.
        Describe the hazards of radiation to humans, the environment, and
        wildlife. Calculate your approximate annual radiation dose and compare
        it to a typical expected dose of someone who works in a nuclear power
        plant. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/Ry2YpGjnakg?si=zaj2augqvJll6mwb"
          target="_blank"
          >What Do Radiation Contamination and Exposure Mean? (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/EuKzI3g5ra4?si=0z8dwKUGPc34S2YD"
          target="_blank"
          >Biological Effects of Radiation (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://www.ans.org/nuclear/dosechart/" target="_blank">
          Radiation Dose Calculator (website)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-11986">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 2. </span>
      Do the following:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-11986 mb-requirement-id-11987">
        (a) Explain the following terms: atom, nucleus, proton, neutron,
        electron, quark, isotope; alpha particle, beta particle, gamma ray,
        X-ray; ionization, radioactivity, radioisotope, and stability. <br /><i
          >Resources:</i
        >
        <a href="https://nplab.webspace.durham.ac.uk/glossary/" target="_blank"
          >Glossary of Nuclear Science Terms (website)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/faB9Gb7bl9I?si=Et7Yi1cp8zLvyppP"
          target="_blank"
          >What Are Isotopes? (video)</a
        >
        <br />
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/LraNu_78sCw?si=o4zrlNUwhUT69eB6"
          target="_blank"
          >Quarks Explained (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-11986 mb-requirement-id-11988">
        (b) Choose an element from the periodic table. Construct 3-D models for
        the atoms of three isotopes of this element, showing neutrons, protons,
        and electrons. Write down the isotope notation for each model including
        the atomic and mass numbers. In a separate model or diagram, explain or
        show how quarks make up protons and neutrons. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://filestore.scouting.org/filestore/Merit_Badge_ReqandRes/Requirement%20Resources/Nuclear%20Science/Isotope%20Model%20Activity.pdf"
          target="_blank"
          >Make a Model of an Isotope (PDF)</a
        ><br />
        <a href="https://isotopes.ans.org/" target="_blank"
          >Interactive Isotopes (website)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-11989">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 3. </span>
      Do ONE of the following; then discuss modern particle physics with your
      counselor:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-11989 mb-requirement-id-11990">
        (a) Visit an accelerator, research lab, or university where scientists
        study the properties of the nucleus or nucleons. <br /><br />
        Resources:<br /><a
          href="https://youtu.be/N3i6CgUHSoc?si=tXJzA1pfqwIYRlXE"
          target="_blank"
        >
          Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory Nuclear Science Division
          (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/nrXhK3Gh5EE?si=kH7N_aBRmhyZOkpJ"
          target="_blank"
          >Inside the World's Largest Science Experiment (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-11989 mb-requirement-id-11991">
        (b) List three particle accelerators and describe several experiments
        that each accelerator performs, including basic science and practical
        applications. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/vIeRLeQq7V4?si=wf3TBAQxCGd1nYA5"
          target="_blank"
          >Particle Accelerators: What Are They, How Do They Work, and Why Are
          They Important to Us? (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-11992">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 4. </span>
      Do TWO of the following; then discuss with your counselor: <br /><i
        >Resource:</i
      >
      <a
        href="https://www.iaea.org/sites/default/files/publications/magazines/bulletin/bull23-4/23405043136.pdf"
        target="_blank"
        >Detecting and Measuring Ionizing Radiation - A Short History (PDF)</a
      >
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-11992 mb-requirement-id-11993">
        (a) Build an electroscope. Show how it works. Place a radiation source
        inside and explain the effect it causes. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/fCpaNzpFhPo?si=VwL6Mi6do8qlSrhI"
          target="_blank"
          >DIY Electroscope (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-11992 mb-requirement-id-11994">
        (b) Make a cloud chamber. Show how it can be used to see the tracks
        caused by radiation. Explain what is happening. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/pewTySxfTQk?si=0aPyTx0YDHrocIAv"
          target="_blank"
          >How to Build a Cloud Chamber! (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/jh7SzrNWGhI?si=C4cCRtQruDkCGpAv"
          target="_blank"
          >Working Cloud Chamber | Exploratorium (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://www.ans.org/file/17977/1/Visualizing%20Radiation%20Poster%202024.pdf%20"
          target="_blank"
          >Visualize Radioactive Decay in a Cloud Chamber (PDF)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-11992 mb-requirement-id-11995">
        (c) Perform an experiment demonstrating half-life. Discuss decay chains.
        <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/fo1tgibNLss?si=K2DrEfEaGW5MSdOR"
          target="_blank"
          >How Radioactive Decay Works | Decay Chains (video)</a
        ><br />
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/mCSXJNVdK0Y?si=A3UPqOjowKtkSmxk"
          target="_blank"
          >Skittles Half Life Lab | Radioactive Isotope Decay | Half Life Graph
          (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-11996">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 5. </span>
      Do ONE of the following; then discuss with your counselor the principles
      of radiation safety:
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-11996 mb-requirement-id-11997">
        (a) Using a radiation survey meter and a radioactive source, show how
        the counts per minute change as the source gets closer to or farther
        from the radiation detector. Place three different materials between the
        source and the detector, then explain any differences in the
        measurements per minute. Explain how time, distance, and shielding can
        reduce an individual's radiation dose. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://filestore.scouting.org/filestore/Merit_Badge_ReqandRes/Requirement%20Resources/Nuclear%20Science/shutterstock_1169023357.pdf"
          target="_blank"
          >How Materials Shield Radiation (PDF)</a
        >
        <br />
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/bNSKIbRNy3c?si=3WqSseNb_EbOeZAx"
          target="_blank"
          >Time, Distance and Shielding (video)</a
        >
        <br />
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/GdZD_hJBdOE?si=p4mOulsJpBxDWH5j"
          target="_blank"
          >Measuring Radiation (video)</a
        >
        <br />
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/0-Yaeh3dOZk?si=Z1MokzEOznMdvlZD"
          target="_blank"
          >Using a Survey Meter: CPM vs Distance (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-11996 mb-requirement-id-11998">
        (b) Describe how radon is detected in homes. Discuss the steps taken for
        the long-term and short-term test methods, tell how to interpret the
        results, and explain when each type of test should be used. Explain the
        health concerns related to radon gas and tell what steps can be taken to
        reduce radon in buildings. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/24aoot_CwoM?si=IYOyLpbVk2z2fb4R"
          target="_blank"
          >What is Radon, Anyway? (video)</a
        >
        <br />
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/SlRVdKdTBFE?si=pJrBWumWDON3uPcG"
          target="_blank"
          >How Dangerous Is Radon to Your Health? (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-11996 mb-requirement-id-11999">
        (c) Visit a place where X-rays are used. Draw a floor plan of this room.
        Show where the unit, the unit operator, and the patient would be when
        the X-ray unit is operated. Explain the precautions taken and the
        importance of those precautions. <br /><i>Resource:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/-pwY3-7lJJg?si=qctALb5U-IM9vG-K"
          target="_blank"
          >X-Ray Room Tour || Ask the Rad Tech (video)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
  </div>
  <div class="mb-requirement-item">
    <div class="mb-requirement-parent mb-requirement-id-12000">
      <span class="mb-requirement-listnumber"> 6. </span>
      Do ONE of the following; then discuss with your counselor how nuclear
      energy is used to produce electricity: <br /><br />Resource:<br />
      <a href="https://www.ans.org/nuclear/energy/" target="_blank"
        >Nuclear Energy (website)</a
      >
    </div>
    <ul class="mb-requirement-children-list">
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12000 mb-requirement-id-12001">
        (a) Make a drawing showing how nuclear fission happens. Observe a
        mousetrap reactor (setup by an adult) and use it to explain how a chain
        reaction could be started. Explain how a chain reaction could be stopped
        or controlled in a nuclear reactor. Explain what is meant by a "critical
        mass." <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/O2pyRDQgVjk?si=xYh6mItbfRQoaWqN"
          target="_blank"
          >What Really Happened the First Time We Split a Heavy Atom in Half
          (video)</a
        >
        <br />
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/czjAtx8GjjA?si=l0xUwP2x5pJyQB85"
          target="_blank"
          >What is Critical Mass | Nuclear Chain Reaction| Fission Chain
          Reaction| Critical Mass Of Uranium (video)</a
        >
        <br />
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/vjqIJW_Qr3c?si=VFFlUgoPcuDMwqWh"
          target="_blank"
          >Mousetrap Fission (video)</a
        >
      </li>
      <li class="mb-requirement-child mb-parent-12000 mb-requirement-id-12002">
        (b) Visit a local nuclear power plant or nuclear reactor either in
        person or online (with your parent or guardian's permission). Learn how
        a reactor works and how the plant generates electricity. Find out what
        percentage of electricity in the United States is generated by nuclear
        power plants, by coal, and by gas. <br /><i>Resources:</i>
        <a
          href="https://youtu.be/6K5gy3RLcKc?si=sJl0OAEvTIGX7Pq-"
          target="_blank"
          >What Is Nuclear Energy? Shrink Down to an Atom and Find Out
          (video)</a
        >
        <br />
        <a href="https://www.eia.gov/consumption/" target="_blank"
          >Energy Consumption &amp; Efficiency Data | Energy Information Agency
          (website)</a
        >
      </li>
    </ul>
    <div style="padding-left: 10px; font-size: 14px; color: #515354"></div>
    <br />
